y.admin.inc:841','default','Deleting a term will delete all its children if there are any. This action cannot be undone.','','none'),(3034,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:873','default','Are you sure you want to delete the vocabulary %title?','','none'),(3035,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:876','default','Deleting a vocabulary will delete all the terms in it. This action cannot be undone.','','none'),(3036,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:908','default','Are you sure you want to reset the vocabulary %title to alphabetical order?','','none'),(3037,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:911','default','Resetting a vocabulary will discard all custom ordering and sort items alphabetically.','','none'),(3038,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:202;203','default','Created new vocabulary %name.','','none'),(3039,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:203;207;769;773;855;889;924','default','taxonomy','','7.21'),(3040,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:206;207','default','Updated vocabulary %name.','','none'),(3041,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:418;445;912','default','Reset to alphabetical','','none'),(3042,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:768;769','default','Created new term %term.','','none'),(3043,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:772;773','default','Updated term %term.','','none'),(3044,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:854;855','default','Deleted term %name.','','none'),(3045,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:888;889','default','Deleted vocabulary %name.','','none'),(3046,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.admin.inc:923;924','default','Reset vocabulary %name to alphabetical order.','','none'),(3047,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:13','default','administer taxonomy','','7.21'),(3048,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:127','default','Add vocabulary','','7.21'),(3049,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:137','default','Edit vocabulary','','none'),(3050,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:146','default','Edit term','','none'),(3051,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:163','default','Autocomplete taxonomy','','none'),(3052,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:170','default','List terms','','none'),(3053,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:185','default','Add term','','none'),(3054,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:421','default','- None selected -','','none'),(3055,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:424','default','- None -','','7.21'),(3056,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:520','default','A comma-separated list of terms describing this content. Example: funny, bungee jumping, \"Company, Inc.\".','','none'),(3057,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:551','default','Vocabularies','','none'),(3058,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:638','default','The %name vocabulary can not be modified in this way.','','none'),(3059,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1163','default','There are currently no posts in this category.','','none'),(3060,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1266','default','The taxonomy module allows you to categorize content using various systems of classification. Free-tagging vocabularies are created by users on the fly when they submit posts (as commonly found in blogs and social bookmarking applications). Controlled vocabularies allow for administrator-defined short lists of terms as well as complex hierarchies with multiple relationships between different terms. These methods can be applied to different content types and combined together to create a powerful and flexible method of classifying and presenting your content.','','none'),(3061,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1267','default','For example, when creating a recipe site, you might want to classify posts by both the type of meal and preparation time. A vocabulary for each allows you to categorize using each criteria independently instead of creating a tag for every possible combination.','','none'),(3062,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1268','default','Type of Meal: <em>Appetizer, Main Course, Salad, Dessert</em>','','none'),(3063,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1269','default','Preparation Time: <em>0-30mins, 30-60mins, 1-2 hrs, 2hrs+</em>','','none'),(3064,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1270','default','Each taxonomy term (often called a \'category\' or \'tag\' in other systems) automatically provides lists of posts and a corresponding RSS feed. These taxonomy/term URLs can be manipulated to generate AND and OR lists of posts classified with terms. In our recipe site example, it then becomes easy to create pages displaying \'Main courses\', \'30 minute recipes\', or \'30 minute main courses and appetizers\' by using terms on their own or in combination with others. There are a significant number of contributed modules which you to alter and extend the behavior of the core module for both display and organization of terms.','','none'),(3065,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1271','default','Terms can also be organized in parent/child relationships from the admin interface. An example would be a vocabulary grouping countries under their parent geo-political regions. The taxonomy module also enables advanced implementations of hierarchy, for example placing Turkey in both the \'Middle East\' and \'Europe\'.','','none'),(3066,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1272','default','The taxonomy module supports the use of both synonyms and related terms, but does not directly use this functionality. However, optional contributed or custom modules may make full use of these advanced features.','','none'),(3067,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1273','default','For more information, see the online handbook entry for <a href=\"@taxonomy\">Taxonomy module</a>.','','none'),(3068,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1276','default','The taxonomy module allows you to categorize your content using both tags and administrator defined terms. It is a flexible tool for classifying content with many advanced features. To begin, create a \'Vocabulary\' to hold one set of terms or tags. You can create one free-tagging vocabulary for everything, or separate controlled vocabularies to define the various properties of your content, for example \'Countries\' or \'Colors\'.','','none'),(3069,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1277','default','Use the list below to configure and review the vocabularies defined on your site, or to list and manage the terms (tags) they contain. A vocabulary may (optionally) be tied to specific content types as shown in the <em>Type</em> column and, if so, will be displayed when creating or editing posts of that type. Multiple vocabularies tied to the same content type will be displayed in the order shown below. To change the order of a vocabulary, grab a drag-and-drop handle under the <em>Name</em> column and drag it to a new location in the list. (Grab a handle by clicking and holding the mouse while hovering over a handle icon.) Remember that your changes will not be saved until you click the <em>Save</em> button at the bottom of the page.','','none'),(3070,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1282','default','%capital_name is a free-tagging vocabulary. To change the name or description of a term, click the <em>edit</em> link next to the term.','','none'),(3071,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1286','default','%capital_name is a flat vocabulary. You may organize the terms in the %name vocabulary by using the handles on the left side of the table. To change the name or description of a term, click the <em>edit</em> link next to the term.','','none'),(3072,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1288','default','%capital_name is a single hierarchy vocabulary. You may organize the terms in the %name vocabulary by using the handles on the left side of the table. To change the name or description of a term, click the <em>edit</em> link next to the term.','','none'),(3073,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1290','default','%capital_name is a multiple hierarchy vocabulary. To change the name or description of a term, click the <em>edit</em> link next to the term. Drag and drop of multiple hierarchies is not supported, but you can re-enable drag and drop support by editing each term to include only a single parent.','','none'),(3074,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1293','default','Define how your vocabulary will be presented to administrators and users, and which content types to categorize with it. Tags allows users to create terms when submitting posts by typing a comma separated list. Otherwise terms are chosen from a select list and can only be created by users with the \"administer taxonomy\" permission.','','none'),(3075,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1332','default','After saving a new term to the database','','none'),(3076,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1335','default','After saving an updated term to the database','','none'),(3077,'modules/taxonomy/taxonomy.module:1338','default','After deleting a term','','none'),(3078,'modules/throttle/throttle.admin.inc:21','default','Auto-throttle on anonymous users','','none'),(3079,'modules/throttle/throttle.admin.inc:25','default','The congestion control throttle can be automatically enabled when the number of anonymous users currently visiting your site exceeds the specified threshold. For example, to start the throttle when your site has 250 anonymous users online at once, enter \'250\' in this field. Leave this value blank or set to \"0\" if you do not wish to auto-throttle on anonymous users. You can inspect the current number of anonymous users using the \"Who\'s online\" block.','','none'),(3080,'modules/throttle/throttle.admin.inc:29','default','Auto-throttle on authenticated users','','none'),(3081,'modules/throttle/throttle.admin.inc:33','default','The congestion control throttle can be automatically enabled when the number of authenticated users currently visiting your site exceeds the specified threshold. For example, to start the throttle when your site has 50 registered users online at once, enter \'50\' in this field. Leave this value blank or set to \"0\" if you do not wish to auto-throttle on authenticated users. You can inspect the current number of authenticated users using the \"Who\'s online\" block.','','none'),(3082,'modules/throttle/throttle.admin.inc:37','default','Auto-throttle probability limiter','','none'),(3083,'modules/throttle/throttle.admin.inc:40','default','The auto-throttle probability limiter is an efficiency mechanism to statistically reduce the overhead of the auto-throttle. The limiter is expressed as a percentage of page views, so for example if set to the default of 10% we only perform the extra database queries to update the throttle status 1 out of every 10 page views. The busier your site, the lower you should set the limiter value.','','none'),(3084,'modules/throttle/throttle.admin.inc:50;53','default','%value is not a valid auto-throttle setting. Please enter a positive numeric value.','','none'),(3085,'modules/throttle/throttle.info:0','default','Handles the auto-throttling mechanism, to control site congestion.','','none'),(3086,'modules/throttle/throttle.module:12','default','Control how your site cuts out content during heavy load.','','none'),(3087,'modules/throttle/throttle.module:87','default','1 user accessing site; throttle enabled.','','none'),(3088,'modules/throttle/throttle.module:87','default','@count users accessing site; throttle enabled.','','none'),(3089,'modules/throttle/throttle.module:87','default','@count[2] users accessing site; throttle enabled.','','none'),(3090,'modules/throttle/throttle.module:95','default','1 guest accessing site; throttle enabled.','','none'),(3091,'modules/throttle/throttle.module:95','default','@count guests accessing site; throttle enabled.','','none'),(3092,'modules/throttle/throttle.module:95','default','@count[2] guests accessing site; throttle enabled.','','none'),(3093,'modules/throttle/throttle.module:104,  modules/user/user.module:778;781','default','1 user','','none'),(3094,'modules/throttle/throttle.module:104,  modules/user/user.module:778;781','de